{"type": "root", "attrs": {"bestbet": "python script scripting"}, "body": [{"level": 0, "type": "title", "indent": 0, "text": ["Python scripting"], "extent": [0, 21]}, {"type": "summary", "indent": 0, "text": ["How to script Houdini using Python and the Houdini Object Model."], "extent": [56, 128]}, {"level": 2, "id": null, "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 0, "text": ["Overview"], "extent": [128, 143], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 0, "text": ["The Houdini Object Model (HOM) is an application programming interface\n(API) that lets you get information from and control Houdini using the\n", {"scheme": null, "value": "http://www.python.org/", "type": "link", "text": ["Python scripting language"], "exists": true}, ". HOM replaces the\nfunctionality of Houdini\u2019s previous command language, ", {"scheme": null, "value": "/commands/", "type": "link", "text": ["HScript"], "fullpath": "/commands/index"}, "."], "extent": [143, 432]}, {"type": "para", "indent": 0, "text": ["In Python, the ", {"scheme": null, "value": "/hom/hou/index", "type": "link", "text": ["hou package"], "fullpath": "/hom/hou/index"}, " is the top of a hierarchy of modules, functions, \nand classes that define the HOM. The ", {"type": "code", "text": ["hou"]}, " module is automatically imported \nwhen you are writing expressions in the ", {"scheme": null, "value": "/ref/panes/parms", "type": "link", "text": ["parameter editor"], "fullpath": "/ref/panes/parms"}, " \nand in the ", {"type": "code", "text": ["hython"]}, " command-line shell."], "extent": [432, 722]}]}, {"level": 2, "id": null, "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 0, "text": ["Which Python?"], "extent": [722, 742], "body": [{"type": "platform_group", "body": [{"ext": null, "type": "platform", "indent": 0, "text": ["Mac"], "role": "item", "extent": [742, 757], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["On Mac OS X, Houdini uses the system\u2019s Python."], "extent": [757, 809]}], "container": true}, {"ext": null, "type": "platform", "indent": 0, "text": ["Windows"], "role": "item", "extent": [809, 827], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["On Windows, Houdini uses the version of Python installed with Houdini."], "extent": [827, 903]}], "container": true}, {"ext": null, "type": "platform", "indent": 0, "text": ["Linux"], "role": "item", "extent": [903, 919], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["On Linux, Houdini does not look at ", {"type": "code", "text": ["$PATH"]}, " when trying to search and load the Python library. Instead it searches all the paths in ", {"type": "code", "text": ["$LD_LIBRARY_PATH"]}, ", then ", {"type": "code", "text": ["/lib"]}, ", and then ", {"type": "code", "text": ["/usr/lib"]}, ". If it can\u2019t find a suitable Python library in the system, it uses the one in ", {"type": "code", "text": ["$HFS"]}, ". If your Python library is not in a standard location, you should add its directory path to ", {"type": "code", "text": ["$LD_LIBRARY_PATH"]}, ". "], "extent": [919, 1307]}], "container": true}], "container": true, "role": "item_group"}]}, {"level": 1, "id": "subtopics", "container": true, "type": "subtopics_section", "indent": 0, "role": "section", "extent": [1307, 1318], "body": [{"type": "col_group", "body": [{"ext": null, "type": "col", "indent": 0, "role": "item", "extent": [1318, 1325], "body": [{"level": 2, "id": null, "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 4, "text": ["Getting started"], "extent": [1325, 1351], "body": [{"type": "subtopics_item_group", "body": [{"ext": null, "type": "subtopics_item", "indent": 4, "text": [" ", {"scheme": null, "value": "intro", "type": "link", "text": "", "fullpath": "/hom/intro"}], "role": "item", "extent": [1351, 1367]}, {"ext": null, "type": "subtopics_item", "indent": 4, "text": [" ", {"scheme": null, "value": "expressions", "type": "link", "text": "", "fullpath": "/hom/expressions"}], "role": "item", "extent": [1367, 1388]}, {"ext": null, "type": "subtopics_item", "indent": 4, "te